args: Is that the third scion of Alberia?!\nPrincess Chelle?!
A member of the royal family's got some\nnerve showing their face here in Raywall.
I'm of the understanding she is to be wed\nto the marquis.
Sending his daughter to curry favor, eh?\nIt's plain as day what the king's thinking!
They certainly don't hold back in this town.\nAnd here I was under the impression this\nwas supposed to be your welcoming party.
Actually, I find it almost refreshing how\nthey wear their true preferences right\non their gilded sleeves.
Still, I suppose it best to educate those\nwho are so woefully unaware of proper\ndecorum during social interaction.
I am so very pleased to make your\nacquaintance, honored guests! I am the\nthird scion of Alberia, Princess Chelle.
What nerve to come over here!\nYou're either fearless or brainless—\nI don't know which.
I simply understand the norms of proper\netiquette, General Bertrand.
I would not dare come to Raywall without\nknowledge of the storied general who\nsingle-handedly leads its military.
May I presume the esteemed personages\nbehind you are Secretary Constantin and\nthe Lady Doriane, Baroness of Bonnard?
Your providence does you credit indeed,\nthat you would study so diligently in effort\nto secure a place in our good graces.
Oh, I've studied other things as well—\nincluding the young artist called Vincent.
Ah! Er...I'm afraid I don't know what\nyou are talking about.
He is said to be a young and nameless\npainter, though of late I hear he built an\natelier most grand. You are unfamiliar?
Goodness, is that so? It was my\nunderstanding that you frequented the\nyoung man's workshop, Baroness.
Eee hee hee! Perhaps it would do simply\nto say that a curious little kitten whispered\nit to me in passing.
Intimidation through blackmail hardly\nbefits one of your standing, Princess.
And such words hardly befit a general.\nOr perhaps you are the sort who charges\ninto battles without strategy or plan?

If you are one to lead such an army,
I would be better served to take the tales
of Raywall's great military with a 
grain of salt—or even the entire shaker.
I say! Princess or no, I will not tolerate\nsuch contempt for Raywall!
I am showing no contempt whatsoever!\nMerely discussing a hypothetical.

If the army is NOT, in fact, a band of
feckless warriors, then I am certain its
general would understand the way
in which I choose to do battle.
I think that's quite enough ＂enthusiasm,＂\nfor one day, everyone.
A pleasure to meet you, Princess Chelle.\nI am the Marquis of Raywall, but I pray\nyou do me the honor of calling me Elua.
Though I suspect you already know of me.
Most certainly—though it casts a decidedly\ndifferent shade in the memory having been\ngreeted in person versus having not.
For example, one might modify\nappropriately their petting of a kitten\nif it were baring its fangs, no?
Gracious me, it seems as though the\nothers here may have carelessly\nstepped upon a dragon's tail.
It would seem so. I apologize for my\nimpropriety, Highness.

Not at all, General. I myself have on
occasion been known to take things rather
too far—let us simply say that there has
been impropriety on both our behalves.

However, I would have you bear in mind
that our feelings towards the royal family
are...complicated. Now then, if you will
please excuse me?
Permit me to greet you once more,\nYour Highness—or perhaps I ought to\nsimply call you my betrothed?

The honor is mine, dear fiancé.
Ah, but my heart has been aflutter,
wondering what sort of man my
husband-in-waiting might turn out to be.
And what are your impressions now that\nyou have beheld the man in person?
They are positive indeed. Beyond that...\nWell, we shall simply have to see how\nthings develop in the days to come.
A most frightening thought;\nI shall endeavor not to disappoint.
And what are your impressions of me?

I am intrigued. If you will forgive me a bit
of bluntness, I had heard you were a rather
self-absorbed princess, and was surprised
this union was allowed to proceed.
You suspected I would never have\nacceded to a political marriage?

I did. However, as it was decided upon
with a surprising degree of readiness,
I felt you were also the type who set aside
her own happiness for that of her house.
Though I might be royalty, in the end I am\nlittle more than a bird in a gilded cage.
So I thought—but your recent exchange\nhas made me reconsider that assumption.
It made me feel as though you are indeed\na woman who knows the meaning of\nnobility—and of being waited upon.
This is but a theory of mine, but I see\nnobility as something not decided by\nthose above, but by those below.
It is only because our vassals and people\nacknowledge us as noble that we\naristocrats can BE noble.

To perpetuate that, we must protect our
vassals and people while maintaining an
environment in which they can quite
readily recognize our nobility.
One such method is a political marriage,\nand I imagine your understanding of this\nfact lead you to acquiesce to our union.
All this time, Lord Elua,\nI have had a thought:
What an efficient thing, political marriage!
So efficient, I think, that there is no\nbetter method for manipulating both\npopular and political sentiment.
Yet even in high society, there are\nmany who avoid such unions, which is\nfoolishness to the extreme.
Such people know nothing and less\nabout what nobility actually is.

Nobility is, by nature, a meaningless
thing. People do not inherently have
degrees of value, yet we impose rank
upon them, and so nobility is born.
Just so. And to ascribe value to such an\nempty thing, we've no avenue other than\nto humor, soothe, and distract.
Indeed, those of noble rank must soothe\nthe people so they might welcome such\npalliatives with gladness in their hearts.
Avoiding what is necessary to accomplish\nthat puts one worlds apart from the notion\nof nobility.
I confess, despite my interest in the\nMarquis of Raywall, I have had little\ninterest in YOU, Lord Elua.
Yet this conversation has set my opinion\nin quite the opposite direction.
I trust I may take that as praise?
You may. Ah, it seems as though I will\nlike this city far more than I anticipated.
